						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Alliance-for-a-Green-Revolution-in-Africa-AGRA" title="Alliance for a Green Revolution in Africa (AGRA) " alt="link">Alliance for a Green Revolution in Africa (AGRA) </a></h2>

	
					<p>AGRA is committed to reducing hunger and poverty in Africa through agricultural development targeted to resource-poor farmers. AGRA will conduct high level policy formation, advocacy and communications, provide access to high level African and global leaders and to donors, and mobilize resources and political commitments for itself and complementary activities. AGRA will be supported by Programs for a Green Revolution in Africa (ProGRA), an organization that is capable of receiving substantial funding for redistribution to improve the productivity and profitability of small-scale farming in Africa. The first major initiative of ProGRA is Program for Africa’s Seed System (PASS) that operates in 20 African countries. PASS includes five projects at a total cost of $150 million over five years, of which the Rockefeller will contribute $50 million and the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation $100 million. See also <a href="http://www.africancrops.net/news/sept06/agra.htm" target="_blank">http://www.africancrops.net/news/sept06/agra.htm</a> </p>
							<p><span class="date">7/02/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Alliance-for-a-Green-Revolution-in-Africa-AGRA">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="article" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Association-of-African-Agricultural-Professionals-in-the-Diaspora-AAAPD" title="Association of African Agricultural Professionals in the Diaspora (AAAPD)" alt="article">Association of African Agricultural Professionals in the Diaspora (AAAPD)</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>The Association of African Agricultural Professionals in the Diaspora (AAAPD) is a new organization founded in 2008 and launched in 2010 at the World Bank, DC with the assistance of the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation. &nbsp;<a href="http://www.aaapd-africa.org/" target="_self">http://www.aaapd-africa.org/</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;It is comprised of a database of multi-disciplinary African Professionals in the Diaspora, many of them academicians, researchers, extension specialists, agricultural economists and development agents. Most of them have 10-20 years’ experience working in different capacities in various regions of Africa in addition to their international experience. AAAPD provides a platform where the Diasporians interact and discuss hot issues affecting African development and solicit novel ideas to develop African agriculture. &nbsp;AAAPD experienced severe technical difficulties with their original website which made it difficult for members to navigate and communicate or for potential members to join. AAAPD thought it prudent to start all over again by switching website developers/providers &nbsp;which we did, and the end product is &nbsp;an entirely new, attractive and easily navigable website ( <a href="http://www.aaapd-africa.org/" target="_blank">www.aaapd-africa.org</a> ). &nbsp;As an original goal, AAAPD tried to develop a comprehensive member database which is dynamic and is easily accessible to all registered members. &nbsp;Unfortunately as they shifted platforms from the old to the new website, some of the pertinent member profile information did not transfer and this is makes it impossible to filtering the database using all member profile parameters. We want to correct this problem as a matter of urgency. It will therefore be greatly appreciated if you could take a few minutes to verify your personal profile and make any necessary changes and updates. In some cases it might be easier, and even more efficient, if you could register as a new member. &nbsp;AAAPD will also continue to update members on the activities of the association through a monthly newsletter. To receive the newsletter, you are required to subscribe via the Subscribe Newsletter link, supply the required information, and you will be able to read the Newsletter from the president each month. &nbsp;&nbsp;Related: PAEPARD supports ARD Diaspora &nbsp;<a href="http://www.aaapd-africa.org/blog_detail/5" target="_blank">http://www.aaapd-africa.org/blog_detail/5</a></p>
							<p><span class="date">4/04/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="article" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Association-of-African-Agricultural-Professionals-in-the-Diaspora-AAAPD">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Association-of-African-Universities-AAU" title="Association of African Universities (AAU)" alt="link">Association of African Universities (AAU)</a></h2>

	
					<p>Association of African Universities, the pan-African organization promoting cooperation between universities. The AAU site provides links to all participating universities, and the Database of African Theses and Dissertations (DATAD), an initiative to improve access to African scholarly work.</p>
							<p><span class="date">15/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Association-of-African-Universities-AAU">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/AU-IBAR-African-Union-Interafrican-Bureau-for-Animal-Resources" title="AU/IBAR - African Union/Interafrican Bureau for Animal Resources" alt="link">AU/IBAR - African Union/Interafrican Bureau for Animal Resources</a></h2>

	
					<p> The mandate of AU/IBAR is to enhance AU member states and their regional economic communities to sustainably improve the contribution of animal resources to the nutrition and incomes of their communities, especially the rural poor. This mandate has been organized into three core strategic programme thrusts (animal health, animal production and trade and markets) that are supported by cross-cutting pillars covering livestock information, communication and knowledge management, quality assurance of livestock and products of animal origin and the harmonization of livestock related policies and legal framework. AU/IBAR has given top priority to the control of the highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) as well as major transboundary animal diseases such as rinderpest, African swine fever, contagious bovine pleuropneumonia (CBPP), foot-and-mouth disease (FMD), peste des petits ruminants (PPR), Newcastle disease, and the African horse sickness.</p>
							<p><span class="date">25/05/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/AU-IBAR-African-Union-Interafrican-Bureau-for-Animal-Resources">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/BioCassava-Plus" title="BioCassava Plus" alt="link">BioCassava Plus</a></h2>

	
					<p>BioCassava Plus is an integrated team of scientists whose objective is to reduce malnutrition by delivering improved cassava cultivars that provide complete and balanced nutrition in readily marketable and higher yielding food crop. Over 250 million sub-Saharan Africans rely on cassava as their major source of calories. A cassava-based diet does not provide complete nutrition, however. BioCassava Plus aims to reduce malnutrition by delivering more nutritious, higher yielding, and more marketable cultivars of cassava. The improved traits which we will deliver include: enhanced bioavailable levels of zinc, iron, protein, vitamin A, vitamin E, and reduced quantities of toxic cyanogenic glycosides, improved post-harvest durability, and improved resistance against viral diseases. Field and human feeding trials will be conducted in close collaboration with African scientists to demonstrate efficacy. BioCassava Plus is funded by the Grand Challenges in Global Health initiative, a partnership dedicated to supporting scientific and technical research to solve critical health problems in the developing world. The initiative's partners are the Bill &amp; Melinda Gates Foundation, the Canadian Institutes of Health Research, the Foundation for the National Institutes of Health, and the Wellcome Trust.</p>
							<p><span class="date">20/02/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/BioCassava-Plus">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Biopact" title="Biopact" alt="link">Biopact</a></h2>

	
					<p>The Biopact is a Brussels-based connective of European and African citizens who strive towards the establishment of a mutually beneficial ‘energy relationship’ based on biofuels and bioenergy. For the time being, Biopact is a volunteer effort, but the young organisation is working towards formalisation under a non-profit structure because of growing interest in its activities and its vision. The group’s activities currently consist of building a web presence, delivering basic consulting services to the media and to bioenergy projects in the South, and of networking with other organisations. The site features a database of news items on many biofuel crops.</p>
							<p><span class="date">18/07/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Biopact">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/CGIAR-Generation-Challenge-Programme" title="CGIAR Generation Challenge Programme" alt="link">CGIAR Generation Challenge Programme</a></h2>

	
					<p>This is a research and capacity-building network that uses plant genetic diversity, advanced genomic science and comparative biology to develop tools and technologies that enable plant breeders in the developing world to produce better crop varieties for resource-poor farmers. The GCP is one of four Challenge Programmes established by the CGIAR to make high impacts in the short term through thematic approaches involving a multitude of research, development, health and delivery organisations. The Challenge Programmes are time-bound, independently governed programmes which address themes of overwhelming global importance and need: nutrition, water use efficiency and conservation, crop genetic diversity and the Sub-Saharan Africa region. The hallmarks of the Challenge Programmes are their collaborative approach, thematic orientation and a time limit – 10 years for each. The Generation Challenge Programme has five subprogrammes that span the spectrum of research in germplasm, genomics, bioinformatics and molecular breeding for agricultural development: genetic diversity of global genetic resources; comparative genomics for gene discovery; trait capture for crop improvement; bioinformatics and crop information systems; and capacity-building and enabling delivery.</p>
							<p><span class="date">5/10/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/CGIAR-Generation-Challenge-Programme">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Climate-Change-Adaptation-in-Africa-CCAA-Increasing-African-participation-in-the-Climate-Change-dialog" title="Climate Change Adaptation in Africa (CCAA) – Increasing African participation in the Climate Change dialog" alt="link">Climate Change Adaptation in Africa (CCAA) – Increasing African participation in the Climate Change dialog</a></h2>

	
					<p>The DFID-funded Climate Change Adaptation in Africa program aims to improve the capacity of African countries to adapt to climate change in ways that benefit the most vulnerable. A range of program activities now support this goal, including increasing African participation in regional and international gatherings. Specifically, the CCAA program is looking to provide financial assistance to institutions that facilitate African attendance at given conferences or meetings to strengthen their capacity to contribute to climate change adaptation in Africa. Meetings, whose themes and objectives are in line with the CCAA’s program, are eligible and will be evaluated using the criteria listed on the website. For information about funding criteria and applications, visit the <a href="http://www.idrc.ca/ccaa" target="_blank">IDRC website</a>. See also the inception workshop report: <a href="http://www.research4development.info/projectsAndProgrammes.asp?OutputID=175177" target="_blank">Towards a Regional Strategy in Climate Change Adaptation: Sharing Knowledge on Climate Risks and Adaptation Options.</a> Co-hosted by: <a href="http://www.research4development.info/ProjectsAndProgrammes.asp?projectID=60055" target="_blank">UNECA and IDRC Climate Change Adaptation in Africa program</a>, Addis Ababa, April 16–20, 2007</p>
							<p><span class="date">23/04/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Climate-Change-Adaptation-in-Africa-CCAA-Increasing-African-participation-in-the-Climate-Change-dialog">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Competence-Platform-on-Energy-Crop-and-Agroforestry-Systems-for-Arid-and-Semi-arid-Ecosystems-Africa-COMPETE" title="Competence Platform on Energy Crop and Agroforestry Systems for Arid and Semi-arid Ecosystems – Africa (COMPETE)" alt="link">Competence Platform on Energy Crop and Agroforestry Systems for Arid and Semi-arid Ecosystems – Africa (COMPETE)</a></h2>

	
					<p>COMPETE will bring together world-leading scientists, researchers, funders and practitioners from different fields and across the world to create a platform for discussion, knowledge exchange, policy and methodology development. It will use this expertise to provide strategic and practical guidance and tools on the provision of modern bioenergy for the sustainable and optimal usage of these special ecosystems. A number of sub-objectives which represent the highly cross-sectoral nature of bioenergy provision and the breadth and depth of the scientific and technological objectives that COMPETE will integrate into providing useful decision making and implementation tools. COMPETE is funded by the EU under FP6.</p>
							<p><span class="date">18/07/2007</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Competence-Platform-on-Energy-Crop-and-Agroforestry-Systems-for-Arid-and-Semi-arid-Ecosystems-Africa-COMPETE">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Coordination-and-Advancement-of-sub-Saharan-Africa-EU-Science-and-Technology-Cooperation-Network-CAAST-Net" title="Coordination and Advancement of sub-Saharan Africa-EU Science and Technology Cooperation Network (CAAST-Net)" alt="link">Coordination and Advancement of sub-Saharan Africa-EU Science and Technology Cooperation Network (CAAST-Net)</a></h2>

	
					<p>CAAST-Net is a new four-year joint EU-Africa science and technology policy dialogue and cooperation project funded by the EU’s Seventh Framework Programme. CAAST-Net has been developed against the background of a global consensus that capacity in science and technology is essential not only to economic competitiveness, but also to sustainable development and poverty reduction. The goal is to promote and facilitate cooperation in science and technology, primarily, although not exclusively focusing on greater use of the FP7, and aiming for greater synergy between R&amp;D and development cooperation instruments such as the European Development Fund. Many of CAST-Net’s activities, such as brokerage events, conferences, information days and thematic discussion platforms will be open to interested parties from Africa and the EU. For more information, and to express interest in participating in CAAST-Net activities, contact <a href="mailto:a.cherry@acu.ac.uk" target="_self">Dr Andy Cherry </a>at the Association of Commonwealth Universities, London: tel: +44 (0)20 7380 6746.</p>
							<p><span class="date">18/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Coordination-and-Advancement-of-sub-Saharan-Africa-EU-Science-and-Technology-Cooperation-Network-CAAST-Net">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Educating-Africa" title="Educating Africa " alt="link">Educating Africa </a></h2>

	
					<p>EducatingAfrica.com is a foundation committed to introducing cost-effective and sensible education initiatives and in addition acknowledge some of the tremendous educational projects that have been introduced in Southern Africa. The initial focus is on Southern Africa but once the initiatives have been introduced then it is hoped that they can be expanded throughout Africa. It is apparent that there are superb educational ideas, generous benefactors and intellectual capital and able to be invested in worthwhile educational projects. However, often there is a mismatch in linking the various groups. EducatingAfrica.com hopes to match up the various groups. One project, <a href="http://www.teachamantofish.org.uk/projects.php" target="_blank">TeachAManToFish</a>, is working to improve the relevance, quality, and availability of agricultural education in developing countries. The approach uses school businesses to teach entrepreneurship and agricultural skills – and earning schools extra income to support their costs.</p>
							<p><span class="date">18/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Educating-Africa">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Forum-for-Agricultural-Research-in-Africa-FARA" title="Forum for Agricultural Research in Africa (FARA)" alt="link">Forum for Agricultural Research in Africa (FARA)</a></h2>

	
					<p>FARA is the Forum for Agricultural Research in Africa, an umbrella organization bringing together and forming coalitions of major stakeholders in agricultural research and development in Africa. FARA complements the innovative activities of national, international and sub-regional research institutions by delivering services that are more responsive and effective to its stakeholders. It plays advocacy and coordination roles for agricultural and agroforestry research for development, while the national agricultural research systems (NARSs), advanced research institutions (ARIs) and international agricultural research centres (IARCs) develop improved technologies along the research-to-development continuum in their respective countries and coverage areas. </p>
							<p><span class="date">8/06/2010</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Forum-for-Agricultural-Research-in-Africa-FARA">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Henry-Doubleday-Research-Association-HDRA" title="Henry Doubleday Research Association (HDRA)" alt="link">Henry Doubleday Research Association (HDRA)</a></h2>

	
					<p>The international programme of the HDRA, or Garden Organic, focuses on development research &amp; capacity building. Our research activities aim to establish sustainable agriculture and agroforestry systems in developing countries, working with rural, urban and peri-urban farming systems in many countries including Cuba, Cape Verde, South Africa, Kenya, Ghana, Zambia and the West Indies. Programmes focus on research and training in the management &amp; utilisation of Prosopis; working with networks, organisations and farmers to build capacity for ecological agriculture; crop production and agroforestry – green manures, composts, manures, rotations, seed saving and biological controls for sustainable land use; soil fertility and organic waste, including composting, use of animal waste and use of peri-urban waste; and trade – developing organic products for domestic markets and for export.</p>
							<p><span class="date">18/01/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Henry-Doubleday-Research-Association-HDRA">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Information-Communication-and-Technologies-for-Africa-Rural-Development-ICTARD" title="Information Communication and Technologies for Africa Rural Development (ICTARD)" alt="link">Information Communication and Technologies for Africa Rural Development (ICTARD)</a></h2>

	
					<p>ICTARD is using ICTs to eradicate poverty in rural Uganda using a bottom-up approach in its efforts to eradicate poverty and facilitate development. ICTARD secures the donation of ICT tools from private and public corporations, develops solutions using a combination of those ICT tools, designs projects and implements them in developing countries. This is done through capacity building, applying existing ICTs, and developing suitable ICTs solutions to best meet the needs of our target groups </p>
							<p><span class="date">27/10/2006</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Information-Communication-and-Technologies-for-Africa-Rural-Development-ICTARD">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/International-Crops-Research-Institute-for-the-Semi-Arid-Tropics-ICRISAT" title="International Crops Research Institute for the Semi-Arid Tropics (ICRISAT)" alt="link">International Crops Research Institute for the Semi-Arid Tropics (ICRISAT)</a></h2>

	
					<p>International Crops Research Institute for the Semi-Arid Tropics (ICRISAT in Africa) is a CGIAR Future Harvest Center for science-based agricultural development in the semi-arid tropics. ICRISAT works in partnership with national research organizations, NGOs, the private sector, etc., to increase the productivity of crops such as sorghum, pearl millet, chickpea, pigeonpea and groundnut. ICRISAT?s Virtual Academy for the Semi-arid Tropics VASAT offers information, best practices and distance education for communities and intermediaries in the dry tropics.</p>
							<p><span class="date">15/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/International-Crops-Research-Institute-for-the-Semi-Arid-Tropics-ICRISAT">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Launch-of-a-new-African-Plant-Breeding-Academy" title="Launch of a new African Plant Breeding Academy" alt="link">Launch of a new African Plant Breeding Academy</a></h2>

	
					<p>The University of California at Davis, in collaboration with the African Union’s New Partnership for Africa’s Development (NEPAD) and the African Orphan Crops Consortium launched the &nbsp;African Plant Breeding Academy. The Academy is designed to train a generation of plant breeders who will help improve the nutritional value of indigenous African crops. The Consortium (of &nbsp;which the Academy is part) aims to sequence the genomes of 96 indigenous orphan crops that are important for African diets (African eggplant, potato, cocoyam, Ethiopian mustard, as well &nbsp;as cassava, cacao, millet, sorghum and legumes, among others). Participating African plant breeders at the new academy will be trained in the most advanced theory and technologies for &nbsp;plant breeding, quantitative genetics, statistics and experimental design, in support of critical decisions for crop improvement.(UC Davis, 20/06/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/07/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/Launch-of-a-new-African-Plant-Breeding-Academy">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/NEPAD-African-Forum-on-Science-and-Technology-for-Development-AFSTD" title="NEPAD: African Forum on Science and Technology for Development (AFSTD)" alt="link">NEPAD: African Forum on Science and Technology for Development (AFSTD)</a></h2>

	
					<p>AFSTD was established by the NEPAD to promote the application of S&amp;T for economic growth and poverty reduction. NEPAD is a pledge by African leaders, based on a common vision and a firm and shared conviction, that they have a pressing duty to eradicate poverty and to place their countries, both individually and collectively, on a path of sustainable growth and development, and at the same time to participate actively in the world economy and body politic. African leaders explicitly recognize that Africa's economic recovery and the transition to sustainable development will not be achieved without investments in science and technology.</p>
							<p><span class="date">15/12/2004</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/S-T-organisations/Africa/Africa-wide-S-T-organizations/NEPAD-African-Forum-on-Science-and-Technology-for-Development-AFSTD">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
											</div> 	
	<br class="cl" />
